# PRISM: Probabilistic Reconstruction of Inhomogeneous Systems Methodology

[![License: MIT](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-yellow.svg)](https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT)
[![Python 3.9+](https://img.shields.io/badge/python-3.9+-blue.svg)](https://www.python.org/downloads/)
[![Code Style: Black](https://img.shields.io/badge/code%20style-black-000000.svg)](https://github.com/psf/black)

**PRISM** is a Bayesian framework designed to bridge the gap between physical dosimetry and radiobiological response in complex, spatially inhomogeneous radiation fields (e.g., Laser-Driven Ion Acceleration, FLASH radiotherapy, Grid therapy).

Unlike traditional methods that assume a uniform dose, PRISM reconstructs the full 3D dose distribution from sparse measurements and propagates dosimetric uncertainties into biological models using an *Error-in-Variables* approach.

## Key Features

* **☢️ Precision Dosimetry:** Gafchromic film processing with multi-channel correction and artifact cleaning (bFDR).
* **🎲 Bayesian Reconstruction:** 3D volume reconstruction from sparse 2D films using Gaussian Processes.
* **🧬 Biological Modeling:** * **Cell Survival:** Linear-Quadratic (LQ) model with dose uncertainty correction.
    * **In-Vivo (Zebrafish):** Voxel-integrated Weibull survival models for complex organisms.
* **📊 Statistical Rigor:** RBE calculation, LOO model comparison, and Prior Sensitivity Analysis.

## Installation

```bash
git clone [https://github.com/yourusername/PRISM-Framework.git](https://github.com/yourusername/PRISM-Framework.git)
cd PRISM-Framework
pip install -r requirements.txt

**Quick Start**

Here is a minimal example of how to reconstruct a 3D dose volume:

from prism.reconstruction import Bayesian3DVolumeReconstructor

# 1. Initialize Reconstructor
recon = Bayesian3DVolumeReconstructor(pdd_folder="data/processed")

# 2. Build 3D Volume from 2D films
recon.build_volume(roi_size_mm=40.0, z_res_mm=0.2)

# 3. Save result
recon.save_volume("results/volume.npz")

